Crimes in San Francisco (2003-14)

Kunal Kumar

Overview

Well conduct some exploratory data analysis on data that records crimes that occurred in San Francisco (SF) between Jan 1,2003 and May 13, 2015. This data set was obtained from SF Open Data via the Kaggle SF Crime Classification challenge.

Data

We will use the train.csv file provided by Kaggle. The original problem requires one to build a model using data from alternate weeks in the 2003-15 time period, and use it to predict crime categories for events in the test.csv file. These events occur in the alternate weeks that are missing from the train.csv file.

Lets explore the data in train.csv

## load packages 
  library(lubridate)  ## manipulating dates
  library(reshape2)   ## manipulating dataframes
  library(TSA)   ## for time series analysis
  library(ggplot2) ## pretty plots

## load data from train.csv. Convert column headings to lower case.
  traindf <- read.csv("train.csv")
  names(traindf) <- tolower(names(traindf))
  names(traindf)
## [1] "dates"      "category"   "descript"   "dayofweek"  "pddistrict"
## [6] "resolution" "address"    "x"          "y"

In train.csv there are 9 fields for each event. Lets get a sense of what these fields are used to record.

  str(traindf)
## 'data.frame':    878049 obs. of  9 variables:
##  $ dates     : Factor w/ 389257 levels "2003-01-06 00:01:00",..: 389257 389257 389256 389255 389255 389255 389255 389255 389254 389254 ...
##  $ category  : Factor w/ 39 levels "ARSON","ASSAULT",..: 38 22 22 17 17 17 37 37 17 17 ...
##  $ descript  : Factor w/ 879 levels "ABANDONMENT OF CHILD",..: 867 811 811 405 405 407 740 740 405 405 ...
##  $ dayofweek : Factor w/ 7 levels "Friday","Monday",..: 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 7 ...
##  $ pddistrict: Factor w/ 10 levels "BAYVIEW","CENTRAL",..: 5 5 5 5 6 3 3 1 7 2 ...
##  $ resolution: Factor w/ 17 levels "ARREST, BOOKED",..: 1 1 1 12 12 12 12 12 12 12 ...
##  $ address   : Factor w/ 23228 levels "0 Block of  HARRISON ST",..: 19791 19791 22698 4267 1844 1506 13323 18055 11385 17659 ...
##  $ x         : num  -122 -122 -122 -122 -122 ...
##  $ y         : num  37.8 37.8 37.8 37.8 37.8 ...

dates, dayofweek, address,x (latitude),y (longitude) tell us the place and time of the event. category has 39 levels such as ARSON, LARCENY/THEFT, etc. descript fleshes out the crime in a little more detail. There are 10 police department districts in SF, and the district in which the crime occurred is recorded in the pddistrict column. resolution lets us know if the perpetrator(s) were arrested, fined, etc.

To make it easier to spot patterns in the data, it will be useful to create columns for week number, month number, and year for each event.

  ## column 1 is the dates column.
  weeknum <- week(traindf[,1])
  ## Note : train set weeks and week() are out of phase. Thus the train set
  ## has all weeknums and not just alternate weeknumstable()
  
  monthnum <- month(traindf[,1])
  year <- year(traindf[,1])
  
  traindf <- cbind(traindf, weeknum, monthnum, year)

Lets plot the total number of crimes each year.

  goldenratio <- 1.618
  p <- qplot(factor(year),data = traindf, geom = "bar", xlab = "Year", ylab = "No. of crimes", main = "Crimes in San Francisco (Jan 2003 - May 2015)")
  p + theme(aspect.ratio = 1/goldenratio)

There is a downward trend from 2003-2011, and then the number of crimes picks up to reach around 2003 levels. Note that only the first five months of data from 2015 are included. This explains the significantly small bar corresponding to 2015.

Lets take a look at the monthly counts in all crimes over the time period Jan 2003 - May2015.

  monthtot <- traindf[,c("dates","category","monthnum","year")]
  
  ## Finding number of events per month for each category and month in 2003-2014. 
  categmonthtot <- tapply(monthtot$monthnum, list(monthtot$category, monthtot$monthnum,
                                                  monthtot$year), function(x) length(x))
  categmonthtot <- melt(categmonthtot)
  
  # replacing NA with 0
  categmonthtot$value[is.na(categmonthtot$value)] <- 0
  names(categmonthtot) <- c("category","monthnum","year","numevt")  
  
  # Character Vector of category names
  categvec <- as.character(unique(categmonthtot$category))
  
  par(mfrow = c(10,4), mar = c(1.5,1.5,1.5,.5),oma = c(2,2,2,0), tcl = -0.3, mgp = c(0,0.2,0), cex.main = 0.95, cex.axis = 0.95)
 
  for(i in 1:39){ tmp.ts <- ts(subset(categmonthtot$numevt, categmonthtot$category == categvec[i]),frequency = 12, start = c(2003,1), end = c(2015,4)); plot.ts(tmp.ts, ylim = c(0,max(tmp.ts)),main = categvec[i], xlab = "",ylab ="") }

  mtext("YEAR", side = 1, outer = T, cex = 1, line = 1, col = "RED")
  mtext("NUMBER OF EVENTS EACH MONTH", side = 2, outer = T, cex = 1, line = 0.8, col = "RED")
  mtext("CRIMES IN SAN FRANCISCO (Jan 2003- April 2015)", side = 3, outer = T, cex = 1, line = 0.8, col = "RED")

An interesting feature in some of the plots are level changes. For example, there is a clear dip in forgery/counterfeiting around 2010. The same feature is seen in VEHICLE THEFT around 2006. We could speculate that it could be related to some change in book-keeping because we see an opposite level change (though of smaller magnitude) in RECOVERED VEHICLE. There also seems to be a level increase in DRIVING UNDER THE INFLUENCE at the start of 2008.

Another interesting feature are isolated peaks. The best example (and perhaps only!) of this seems to be the spike a little after 2008 in LIQUOR LAWS. It seems unlikely that this peak is just an upward fluctuation.
